Install the Rockchip Driver. Download RKDevTool v3.28. Open RKDevTool. Download the SPI Loader. Select the loader and image. Click Run.

Once the basic setup is configured, execute the following commands in the terminal to have everything working properly on the Fydetab: sudo pacman -Syu fydetabduo-post-install reboot Wait until the tablet reboots and enjoy! ğŸ˜Š

æ³¨æ„ Ensure that you have backed up all your data. BredOS images use UEFI boot instead of the original U-Boot. This means you can no longer enter MASKROM mode by pressing the Volume Up + Power keys. Instead, execute the following command in the terminal (THIS WILL COMPLETELY ERASE YOUR DATA): sudo dd if=/dev/urandom of=/dev/mmcblk0 bs=10M count=2 Now the tablet should be in MASKROM mode, and you can flash the standard images. If needed, refer to the Unbrick section in the Fydetab wiki.

Before you begin, ensure you have the following: MicroSD Card USB Dongle USB Drive UEFI Firmware Windows Image
To obtain the correct Windows image for ARM architecture, follow this guide. After downloading the image, use a tool like Rufus to flash the Windows on ARM image to your USB drive.
documents.s: ğŸŒ Getting the Windows Image for ARM

documents.t: Download the UEFI Firmware: Get the latest UEFI firmware for Fydetab Duo from the official repository. Prepare the MicroSD Card: Use a tool like Balena Etcher or Rufus to flash the UEFI firmware onto your MicroSD card. Insert the MicroSD Card: Carefully insert the MicroSD card into the Fydetab Duo, but leave it slightly protrudingâ€”do not fully insert it. Boot into UEFI: Power on your device, and it should boot directly into the UEFI interface.
documents.s: ğŸ’¾ Flashing the UEFI Firmware to Your SD Card

documents.t: Plug in the USB Dongle. Connect Power: Attach the power cable to the USB dongle to ensure sufficient power supply. Insert the USB Drive: Plug the prepared USB drive into the dongle. Boot Windows: Power on your device, and it will boot into Windows on ARM.
